Title: Failing to levitate in the studio
Parallel Stress
Description: Parallel Stress is the documentation of two actions Oppenheim performed in New York State in May 1970. The work comprises two individually framed black and white photographs and a section of typewritten text on blue paper, also framed, that are displayed in a column, one above another. In the first action, shown in the upper side, the artist stretched his body between a masonry-block wall and a collapsed concrete pier at a location between Brooklyn and Manhattan bridges in New York City. He held this position for ten minutes, straining against the pull of gravity to maintain a horizontal position. According to the text, the photograph was taken at the ‘greatest stress position prior to collapse’. The image shows the artist’s body curving downwards between his arms and hands – gripping one set of breeze blocks – and his feet – hooked onto another parallel wall also made of breeze blocks. His back arches as he hangs face-down into empty space. The second

Title: The Third Memory
Description.abstract: On August 22, 1972, John Wojtowicz held up a bank in Brooklyn and took its employees hostage.  The news item was broadcast live on TV and covered in the press.  Later, an article published in Life magazine inspired Sidney Lumet to make Dog Day Afternoon, in 1975, with Al Pacino in the leading role.  An ensemble of narratives, press articles, broadcasts, screenplays, through which the event was interpreted, serves as a prologue to a filmed reconstruction.

Title: L'Expédition scintillante
Description.abstract: The exhibition provides the scenario of an expedition.  It stages a series of hypotheses concerning the progress and representation of this collective enterprise.  Each floor of the museum is a stage in the expedition, corresponding to one act of a musical tale.  Act 1: A boat carved in ice is melting. It is both a vehicle and part of the territory to which it might travel.  A radio broadcasts the log of a ship at sea.The room undergoes the climactic changes noted in the log, written by a character from an unfinished novel by Edgar Allan Poe.A topographical operation that transforms the voyage into territory.Act 2:  A nameless mountain whose topography produces music synchronised with a play of light.  A music box composing concerts for penguins.Act 3.  A stage for the performance of the preceding acts. a skating rink of black ice waiting for representation of the event and its program in three acts.

Title: Billboards
Description.abstract: Top: Billboards/ Chantier Barbés-RochechouartBottom:  Billboards/ Little StoryAn advertising billboard is located.  Actors are called in to interpret an everyday scene linked with the site.  The scene is photographed, printed and then stuck onto the billboard.  A new picture of the site is taken that incorporates the billboard.

Format.medium: 10 black and white photographs and statement.
Description.abstract: On December 17, 1972 a photograph was made of Bernd Becher at the instant almost exactly after he had been made to "look like" a priest, a criminal, a lover, an old man, a police man, an artist, "Bernd Becher," a philosopher, a spy and a vice guy... in that order.

Title: Blanche Niege Lucie
Description.note: During a radio interview, Lucie Doléne, the French voice of Snow White, announced her court case against Disney Voice Characters over the rights to her interpretation of the character.  She won her case- which set a precedent for jurisprudence in the matter.  Blanche-Neige Lucie (Snow White Lucie) is a chronicle of snow White's French voice.  In an empty film studio, Lucie Doléne hums "One Day my Prince Will Come" while her story appears in subtitles.

Title: No Ghost Just a Shell
Description.abstract: In 1999 Pierre Huyghe and Philippe Parreno bought the rights to a manga character from a Japanese company specialized in this market.  This is a synopsis of a collective project.The first two episodes, Two Minutes Out of Time and Anywhere Out of the World, are a prologue that introduces a series of films by different artists.Each of these films contributes to the writing of a contemporary fable in which a sign is inhabited by different authors, before freeing itself.  The original character ends up disappearing and takes away its own copyright.Bottom Image: No Ghost Just a Shell/ One Million KindgomsOne Million Kingdoms tells the story of a documentary that is transformed into a fictional tale.  Anlee is its narrator.  The character walks in a landscape made up of the graphic curves produced by her voice.  It moves within what it says.  Its voice is synthetic; it was based on the voice of Neil Armstrong.  2003

Title: Les Grands ensembles
Description.abstract: Les Grands ensemble is the reconstruction of an urban landscape in the late 1970's.The film uses a fixed image showing an urban area at a specific point in time.  There are very subtle and imperceptible variations as the film progresses.  The multiple changes continue without progression, shaping an image that is experienced as a suspension of time.

Title: Performance/ Audience/ Mirror
Description.abstract: Audience members at a public performance sat facing a mirrored wall as Dan Graham, at one point looking into the mirror himself, described their movements; and, at another point, facing the audience, talks about their movements again.  This time his comments are delayed, however, because the audience has already seen their movements in the mirror.  All of this is also videotaped, which, when viewed, becomes yet another layer of participation.Bottom:In Present Continuous Past(s) (1974), viewers experience their own image on mirrors as well as on monitors, thus confounding perception of what is 'real' and what is not.
